description: From Middle English journe, jorney, from Old French jornee, from Medieval Latin diurnata (“a day's work, a day's journey, a fixed day, a day”), from Latin diurnus (“daily”), from diēs (“day”). Displaced native Old English færeld.

entries.meaning: A set amount of travelling, seen as a single unit; a discrete trip, a voyage.
examples: The journey to London takes two hours by train.

entries.meaning: (figurative) Any process or progression likened to a journey, especially one that involves difficulties or personal development.
examples: my journey of dealing with grief

entries.meaning: (obsolete) A day's travelling; the distance travelled in a day.
The weight of finished coins delivered at one time to the Master of the Mint.

verbs.description: journey (third-person singular simple present journeys, present participle journeying, simple past and past participle journeyed)

entries.meaning: To travel, to make a trip or voyage.
